76561198098765289,Recommended,502940,32655574,Posted: 22 June,all,[HOMO]Branflakes107,Become the Dictator of the U.S.S.R. who seems to develope Parkinson's Disease everytime the phone rings.
,Recommended,502940,33158811,Posted: 2 July,all,RoberTime,"Calm Down, Stalin is a simulation game starring, of course, Stalin. This is a simple game involving doing specific things at your desk such as working and reducing stress, all within a span of time to proceed. Your main focus is the Red Button and a timer on the wall to show how much of a threat your enemy is to invading the state. You cannot have the timer reach the top nor can you push the button in each level.Going deeper into gameplay, there are several options of levels to play after finishing the first introductory one. You can choose to proceed to work on the two factors you should worry about, that change between levels based on the one you've selected, as well as your performance. First there is Tiredness, which worsens the ""Stress"" gained in each level, and Stress, which gradually goes higher, can make managing tasks controllable. Tiredness can have major changes by several optional levels. And then there is Integrity which is the respect you have to the state. This can be tweaked if doing tasks correctly or incorrectly. And just like Tiredness, it can be changed significanly through optional levels. As you progress through the story, you unlock more objects and tasks to use later on.Now for my experience playing the game, it was a bit hard to control and getting to know the mouse controls at first. You can pick up objects with the left button, drop with the middle, and right-click to change hands. The game also has controller support but I don't recommend it. As for main gameplay, it was an interesting experience playing through and surviving for a small period of time. But it was also a bit stressful for me considering all the micromanagement you have to do in the later levels. But I love how the music tends to fit the mood of panic. This game's structuring reminds me of others like Five Nights at Freddy's for the element of survival.However, the game can be buggy at times. For example, when you try shooting targets or stamping papers, sometimes it won't confirm the event or I just suck at targets that it's precise. Also sometimes thrown objects can hit the button causing me to reset. The game tries its best to make sure objects don't trigger the button that it doesn't register as a push of it when it lightly touches it, but in unfortunate situations of me playing the final level, I had a few objects get tossed and hit the button. I even had one being tossed high off the screen, and falling directly on the button :CAnyway, aside from Tetris, this is my other favorite Russian-style game. Quite the thrill playing it. Again, sometimes stressful, but it's still a good game if you like political satire. I give Calm Down, Stalin a 7/10"
